<DOC><DOCNO> AP891020-0198 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 2059EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r w AM-SaudiTanks     10-20 0222</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Saudi Tanks,210</SECOND><HEAD>State Promises To Answer 29 House Members On Saudi Tank Sale</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The State Department said Friday it willrespond to questions raised by Majority Leader Richard Gephardt ofMissouri and 28 other House members on the planned $3 billion saleof 315 modern tanks and other military equipment to Saudi Arabia.   In a letter to Secretary of State James A. Baker III onThursday, they asked if the purchase was in the U.S. strategicinterest, what armor would be included and where the tanks would bedeployed.   Rep. Melvin Levine, D-Calif., questioned in an accompanyingletter whether the administration had conducted sufficientconsultation with Congress.   ``In light of the fact that the Saudis have received over $30billion worth of military goods and services in the past eightyears from the U.S.,'' Levine wrote, ``I am troubled that theystill have yet to meet many basic U.S. policy objectives in theMiddle East.''   In a statement Friday, the department's press office called thequestions raised in the letter by the 29 members ``thoughtful andreasonable.'' The statement added: ``We look forward to answeringthem thoroughyl as we continue our consultations with the Hillabout this sale.''   The purchase will go through unless it is rejected by majorityvote of both the Senate and the House.</TEXT></DOC>